message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms are consistent with maternal estrogen withdrawal, a common condition in newborns due to the sudden decrease in maternal estrogen after birth. Congenital adrenal hyperplasia can cause ambiguous genitalia, but there is no evidence of that in this case. External trauma and genitourinary infection are less likely explanations for the symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms suggest maternal estrogen withdrawal, which occurs when high levels of estrogen from the mother cross the placenta and they are suddenly removed when the baby is born. This can lead to vaginal bleeding, breast enlargement, and neonatal acne. Other options, such as congenital adrenal hyperplasia and genitourinary infection, would present with different symptoms. External trauma is unlikely as there is no history of trauma.
